      "meta": null,
      "label": "text",
      "prov": [],
      "orig": "Second, developers changed CPRS to ensure that CPRS shuts down on a time-out—even if an access violation occurs on shut down. If an access violation occurs in CPRS after the Windows activates the screen saver because of inactivity, the CPRS access violation will not display to the user, and the user will not be aware that CPRS attempted to shut down due to inactivity.",
      "text": "Second, developers changed CPRS to ensure that CPRS shuts down on a time-out—even if an access violation occurs on shut down. If an access violation occurs in CPRS after the Windows activates the screen saver because of inactivity, the CPRS access violation will not display to the user, and the user will not be aware that CPRS attempted to shut down due to inactivity.",
      "formatting": {
        "bold": false,
        "italic": false,
        "underline": false,
        "strikethrough": false,
        "script": "baseline"
      },
